\section*{Energy Resources Analysis}

\subsection*{1. Renewable Energy Sources}
\textbf{Advantages:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Inexhaustible nature: Sources like solar and wind provide sustainable energy.
    \item Low environmental impact: Minimal operational carbon emissions ($CO_2 = 0$).
    \item Energy independence: Reduces reliance on imported fuels.
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Disadvantages:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Intermittency: Power availability depends on stochastic meteorological factors.
    \item High capital intensity: Significant initial investment for infrastructure.
    \item Geographical dependence: Site-specific requirements for optimal efficiency.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{2. Non-Renewable Energy Sources}
\textbf{Advantages:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item High energy density: Large energy output per unit mass, $Q/m$.
    \item Reliability: Provides stable baseload power generation independent of weather conditions.
    \item Infrastructure: Mature technology and established supply chains.
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Disadvantages:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Resource depletion: Finite stock $S_t$ over time, $\frac{dS_t}{dt} < 0$.
    \item Environmental degradation: Release of greenhouse gases ($CO_2, CH_4$) leading to global climate change.
    \item Economic volatility: Prices fluctuate based on geopolitical factors and scarcity.
